<body>

<header>
  <div class="header-label">Economics · Topic 3 · Sub-topic 3.1</div>
  <h1>Production Functions,<br>Isoquants &amp; Isocosts</h1>
  <p>Theory of the Firm — Lesson Summary &amp; Practice Quiz</p>
</header>

<nav class="tab-bar">
  <button class="tab-btn active" onclick="switchTab('summary', this)">📖 Lesson Summary</button>
  <button class="tab-btn" onclick="switchTab('quiz', this)">✏️ Practice Quiz</button>
</nav>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ SUMMARY ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="summary" class="panel active">
<div class="summary-wrap">

  <!-- 1. Production Function -->
  <div class="section-card">
    <div class="section-card-header">
      <span class="section-num">01</span>
      <h2>The Production Function</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card-body">
      <p>A firm's <strong>production function</strong> shows the maximum output obtainable from any combination of inputs given a fixed technology.</p>
      <div class="formula-box">
        <span class="label">General Form</span>
        Q = f(K, L)
        <span class="label" style="margin-top:0.5rem">Cobb-Douglas Form</span>
        Q = A · K<sup>α</sup> · L<sup>β</sup>   where A &gt; 0, α, β &gt; 0
      </div>
      <div class="concept-grid">
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Short Run</h4>
          <p>At least one input is fixed. Firms can only vary variable inputs like labor.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Long Run</h4>
          <p>All inputs become variable. Firms can adjust both capital and labor freely.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Fixed Input</h4>
          <p>A production factor whose quantity cannot be changed in the period under analysis.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 2. Marginal & Average Product -->
  <div class="section-card">
    <div class="section-card-header">
      <span class="section-num">02</span>
      <h2>Marginal &amp; Average Product</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card-body">
      <div class="concept-grid">
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Marginal Product of Labor</h4>
          <p>Additional output from one more unit of labor, holding K constant.<br><strong>MP<sub>L</sub> = ∂Q/∂L</strong></p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Marginal Product of Capital</h4>
          <p>Additional output from one more unit of capital, holding L constant.<br><strong>MP<sub>K</sub> = ∂Q/∂K</strong></p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Average Product of Labor</h4>
          <p>Output per unit of labor.<br><strong>AP<sub>L</sub> = Q / L</strong></p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Diminishing Marginal Productivity</h4>
          <p>As more of one input is used (holding others constant), its marginal product eventually falls: ∂²Q/∂L² &lt; 0</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Key relationship:</strong> When MP<sub>L</sub> &gt; AP<sub>L</sub>, average product is rising. When MP<sub>L</sub> &lt; AP<sub>L</sub>, it is falling. They are equal at the maximum of AP<sub>L</sub>.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 3. Stages of Production -->
  <div class="section-card">
    <div class="section-card-header">
      <span class="section-num">03</span>
      <h2>Three Stages of Production</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card-body">
      <div class="stage-row">
        <div class="stage-box stage-1">
          <h4>Stage I</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>TP increasing at increasing rate</li>
            <li>AP rising to maximum</li>
            <li>MP rising then falling</li>
            <li>MP > AP throughout</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-box stage-2">
          <h4>Stage II ⭐ Rational</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>TP increasing at decreasing rate</li>
            <li>AP falling</li>
            <li>MP falling toward zero</li>
            <li>0 ≤ MP &lt; AP</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div class="stage-box stage-3">
          <h4>Stage III</h4>
          <ul>
            <li>TP decreasing from max</li>
            <li>AP still falling</li>
            <li>MP is negative</li>
            <li>Irrational to operate here</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Rational firms operate in Stage II</strong> — where TP is still growing but MP ≥ 0. The precise optimal point within Stage II requires cost information.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 4. Isoquants -->
  <div class="section-card">
    <div class="section-card-header">
      <span class="section-num">04</span>
      <h2>Isoquants &amp; the MRTS</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card-body">
      <p>An <strong>isoquant</strong> shows all (K, L) combinations that produce the same output level Q₀. Key properties:</p>
      <div class="concept-grid" style="margin-top:1rem">
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Negatively Sloped</h4>
          <p>More of one input means less of the other to keep output constant.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Convex to Origin</h4>
          <p>Reflects diminishing MRTS — inputs are imperfect substitutes.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Never Intersect</h4>
          <p>Each isoquant represents a unique output level; intersection would imply contradiction.</p>
        </div>
        <div class="concept-tile">
          <h4>Higher = More Output</h4>
          <p>Isoquants farther from the origin represent higher output levels.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <div class="formula-box" style="margin-top:1.25rem">
        <span class="label">Marginal Rate of Technical Substitution</span>
        MRTS<sub>LK</sub> = −dK/dL|<sub>Q=Q₀</sub> = MP<sub>L</sub> / MP<sub>K</sub>
      </div>
      <div class="key-insight">
        <strong>Diminishing MRTS:</strong> As we move along an isoquant substituting L for K, each additional unit of L replaces less and less K — because L becomes relatively less productive as it increases.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- 5. Returns to Scale -->
  <div class="section-card">
    <div class="section-card-header">
      <span class="section-num">05</span>
      <h2>Returns to Scale</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="section-card-body">
      <p>How output responds when <em>all</em> inputs are scaled up proportionately. For Cobb-Douglas Q = AK<sup>α</sup>L<sup>β</sup>:</p>
      <div class="formula-box" style="margin-top:1rem">
        <span class="label">Homogeneity Test — multiply all inputs by t &gt; 1</span>
        f(tK, tL) = t<sup>h</sup> · f(K, L) = t<sup>h</sup>Q   where h = α + β
      </div>
      <table class="rts-table">
        <thead>
          <tr><th>Condition</th><th>Returns to Scale</th><th>Example (t = 2)</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
          <tr><td>h = α + β = 1</td><td>Constant (CRS)</td><td>Output doubles: 2Q</td></tr>
          <tr><td>h = α + β &gt; 1</td><td>Increasing (IRS)</td><td>Output more than doubles: &gt;2Q</td></tr>
          <tr><td>h = α + β &lt; 1</td><td>Decreasing (DRS)</td><td>Output less than doubles: &lt;2Q</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <div class="key-insight" style="margin-top:1rem">
        <strong>Caution:</strong> The α + β rule only works for Cobb-Douglas. For other production functions (e.g., Q = L<sup>0.5</sup> + K<sup>0.5</sup>), you must directly test by substituting tK and tL.
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

</div>
</div>

<!-- ══════════════════════════════════ QUIZ ══════════════════════════════════ -->
<div id="quiz" class="panel">
<div class="quiz-wrap">

  <div class="quiz-controls">
    <div class="quiz-meta">
